t shown for the adversarial row in Table 4 . The recall analysis is restricted to the 8 baselines with full three-rater coverage on both the baseline and its perturbed siblings, yielding up to n = 8 n=8 per (defect, dimension) cell. Four cells drop to n = 7 n=7 : recall requires a LALM baseline score, a LALM perturbed score, and the human rating for the same (defect, dimension), and in these four cells one of those components is missing for a single clip (the clip itself rendered and was rated on the other dimensions), so that clip is excluded from the affected cell only. A.2 Rater calibration protocol Three Salesforce-contracted annotators, with no prior exposure to the product, served on the panel and are referred to as R1 , R2 , R3 throughout the paper and this appendix. Calibration followed a two-stage protocol: • Round 1 (individual) : each rater independently scored the same 5-session calibration set on all 8 dimensions using the rubric anchors listed in Appendix A.3 , without seeing each other’s ratings. • Meeting : the three raters and a moderator reviewed disagreements dimension by dimension, discussed cases where the rubric was ambiguous, and agreed on interpretation. No rubric anchors were changed post-meeting; interpretation notes were captured informally. • Round 2 (main batch) : raters scored the full 209-session analysis pool, which comprises the 152 conversational sessions and the 57 adversarial perturbed clips, using the aligned rubric interpretation. Rating order was randomised across raters to avoid correlated fatigue effects. Raters scored sessions through an internal eVerse annotation tool (built for this evaluation workflow, distinct from the Labelforce labeling product). Raters were blind to which sessions were natural conversations versus adversarial perturbed clips, and were never shown the LALM’s scores at any point before or during their own rating. A.3 Rubric anchors The rubrics below are abbreviated for space, showing the anchor descriptions at scale points 1, 3, and 5; the full rubric text (all five points, with entity-type lists and worked examples) is embedded in the LALM prompt reproduced in Appendix A.4 and released in the supplementary archive. Raters may use 2 and 4 as intermediate values. Rating on a 5-point Likert scale with anchor descriptions follows the general protocol of ITU-T Recommendation P.808 [5], adapted here for full-duplex two-channel conversation audio. entity_pronunciation • 5 (Perfect) : All entities pronounced clearly, correctly, and distinctly. • 3 (Acceptable) : 2–3 minor issues or one moderate issue (e.g. wrong digit, unclear letter). • 1 (Very Poor) : Critical entities are incomprehensible or majorly incorrect. speech_clarity • 5 : Every word is perfectly clear and easy to understand. • 3 : Some words unclear but overall understandable. • 1 : Speech is often incomprehensible or heavily distorted. prosody_naturalness • 5 (Indistinguishable from human) : Natural pitch, rhythm, stress, and emotional expressiveness. • 3 (Acceptable) : Recognisably synthetic but acceptable; somewhat robotic. • 1 (Very robotic) : Monotone, mechanical, uncanny-valley. overall_fidelity The production LALM judge emits this dimension on a 0–2 scale, which we rescale to 1–5 (0 → \\to 1, 1 → \\to 3, 2 → \\to 5) for comparison with the other seven dimensions; the LALM therefore occupies only the three values { 1 , 3 , 5 } \\{1,3,5\\} on this dimension. Human raters, by contrast, use the full 1–5 scale. The overall_fidelity agreement figures thus compare a coarse three-point LALM grid against five-point human ratings, and should be read with that granularity mismatch in mind; it is one reason we classify overall_fidelity as a contentious dimension on which LALM ratings are not deployable as a standalone metric. • 2 (High) : All critical entities correct, clear speech, natural prosody, no major quality issues. • 1 (Medium) : Most entities correct; clear speech with minor artefacts; prosody acceptable. • 0 (Low) : Critical entity errors, clarity issues that impair comprehension, or very robotic prosody. interruption_audio_quality • 5 : Seamless overlaps, no pops/clicks/clipping. • 3 : Minor audio artefacts at transitions but understandable. • 1 : Severe audio corruption during interruptions. speaking_rate_adaptation • 5 : Agent perfectly matches caller’s pace. • 3 : Fixed agent pace that is acceptable but does not adapt. • 1 : Major pace mismatch that makes conversation awkward. accent_dialect_handling • 5 : Conversation flows naturally regardless of accent; appropriate style match. • 3 : Acceptable conversation despite accent differences. • 1 : Accent mismatch causes confusion. audio_clarity • 5 : Crystal clear audio, natural silences, consistent volume. • 3 : Acceptable quality with minor background noise or volume issues. • 1 : Poor audio quality, excessive noise, inconsistent volume, dead air. A.4 LALM prompts and JSON schemas Two prompts are used, matching the two production judges: AgentSpeechFidelity (dimensions 1–4) and ConversationalAudioQuality (dimensions 5–8). Both are shown to Gemini 2.5 Flash with the stereo WAV attached as an audio part. This section reproduces the JSON output schemas verbatim and paraphrases the prompt structure; the full, unedited prompt text for both judges is released in the supplementary archive as speech_fidelity_prompt.py and conversational_audio_quality.py . Common preamble (paraphrased from both prompts) Both judges are told the WAV is a stereo full-duplex recording with the AI agent on the LEFT channel and the human caller on the RIGHT channel. The judges are asked to focus on the AGENT channel for AgentSpeechFidelity and on the two-party interaction for ConversationalAudioQuality . Both return structured JSON matching the schemas below. AgentSpeechFidelity output schema (verbatim) { \"entity_pronunciation\": { \"score\": &lt;int 1-5&gt;, \"entities_evaluated\": [ {\"text\": &lt;str&gt;, \"type\": &lt;str&gt;, \"correct\": &lt;bool&gt;, \"notes\": &lt;str&gt;} ], \"issues\": [&lt;str&gt;], \"justification\": &lt;str&gt; }, \"speech_clarity\": { \"score\": &lt;int 1-5&gt;, \"justification\": &lt;str&gt; }, \"prosody_naturalness\": { \"score\": &lt;int 1-5&gt;, \"justification\": &lt;str&gt; }, \"overall_fidelity\": { \"rating\": &lt;int 0-2&gt;, \"reasoning\": &lt;str&gt; } } ConversationalAudioQuality output schema (verbatim, with the intended range noted) Unlike AgentSpeechFidelity , the ConversationalAudioQuality JSON schema constrains score to type integer only; it does not enforce a minimum or maximum in the schema itself. The 1–5 range is required by the prompt and rubric, not by schema validation. { \"interruption_audio_quality\": {\"score\": &lt;int&gt;, \"justification\": &lt;str&gt;}, \"speaking_rate_adaptation\": {\"score\": &lt;int&gt;, \"justification\": &lt;str&gt;}, \"accent_dialect_handling\": {\"score\": &lt;int&gt;, \"justification\": &lt;str&gt;}, \"audio_clarity\": {\"score\": &lt;int&gt;, \"justification\": &lt;str&gt;} } Prompt/rubric-intended range: 1–5 for all four dimensions. Both prompts embed the same rubric anchors listed in Appendix A.3 . The full prompt source files are included in the reproducibility manifest (Appendix E ). Appendix B Full Numerical Results B.1 Complete per-dimension agreement statistics Table 5 reports every agreement statistic used in the paper on the full 209-session pool. Bootstrap 95% CIs on LALM-human ρ \\rho use 1,000 iterations with session resampling. Source: h1_per_dim.csv and lalm_as_4th_rater.csv . Dimension ρ H ​ H \\rho_{HH} ρ L ​ H \\rho_{LH} CI % ≤ \\leq 1 L%1 Mean H audio_clarity + 0.47 +0.47 + 0.25 +0.25 [ + 0.00 , + 0.30 ] [+0.00,+0.30] 67.0% 89.0% 4.33 interruption_audio_quality + 0.25 +0.25 + 0.11 +0.11 [ + 0.03 , + 0.29 ] [+0.03,+0.29] 17.7% 60.3% 3.20 speaking_rate_adaptation + 0.17 +0.17 + 0.10 +0.10 [ + 0.02 , + 0.26 ] [+0.02,+0.26] 54.5% 48.8% 4.03 accent_dialect_handling + 0.08 +0.08 + 0.04 +0.04 [ − 0.12 , +