ils the human-human ρ \\rho by a wide margin (0.26), consistent with Section 4.5 ’s finding that this gap is a property of the adversarial-arm audio regime, not of any one model. Dimension ρ H ​ H \\rho_{HH} ρ L ​ H \\rho_{LH} Gap L%1 Mean L Mean H Bias accent_dialect_handling + 0.08 +0.08 + 0.12 +0.12 0.04 95.7% 4.53 4.88 − 0.35 -0.35 audio_clarity + 0.47 +0.47 + 0.21 +0.21 0.26 82.3% 4.14 4.33 − 0.20 -0.20 speech_clarity + 0.01 +0.01 + 0.09 +0.09 0.08 94.3% 4.74 4.43 + 0.30 +0.30 entity_pronunciation + 0.09 +0.09 + 0.18 +0.18 0.09 81.8% 4.57 4.71 − 0.14 -0.14 prosody_naturalness + 0.11 +0.11 + 0.13 +0.13 0.02 92.3% 3.86 3.94 − 0.08 -0.08 interruption_audio_quality + 0.25 +0.25 + 0.40 +0.40 0.15 70.3% 3.74 3.20 + 0.55 +0.55 speaking_rate_adaptation + 0.17 +0.17 + 0.20 +0.20 0.04 69.4% 3.28 4.03 − 0.75 -0.75 overall_fidelity + 0.11 +0.11 + 0.14 +0.14 0.03 74.2% 4.36 4.38 − 0.02 -0.02 Table 6: Per-dimension agreement for gemini-3.5-flash on the same n = 209 n=209 session pool, directly comparable to Table 5 . ρ H ​ H \\rho_{HH} is unchanged from Table 5 (same human raters, same sessions); Gap is | ρ L ​ H − ρ H ​ H | |\\rho_{LH}-\\rho_{HH}| ; L%1 is the LALM-vs-human-mean within-1 proportion; Bias is the mean LALM score minus the mean human score (negative: LALM rates lower than humans on average). Source: h1_per_dim_gemini35flash.csv . Table 7 reports the same statistics for Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview. Rank correlation is comparable to the other two models (5 of 8 dimensions within the 0.07 gap threshold), but simple agreement is weaker on several dimensions because the model’s mean score runs substantially below the human mean: by − 1.52 -1.52 points on audio_clarity, − 1.44 -1.44 on speaking_rate_adaptation, and − 0.80 -0.80 or lower on three further dimensions (overall_fidelity, accent_dialect_handling, entity_pronunciation). Three dimensions (audio_clarity, speaking_rate_adaptation, overall_fidelity) fall below the 60% within-1 threshold as a direct consequence, mos