merican-2 (dual-conversation), which share the broad American accent family and codec setting but differ in persona; we note the persona effect is not fully isolated from the American-1/American-2 accent difference, so this decomposition is indicative rather than a clean persona contrast. Neutral baseline is the same-persona same-codec across-accent delta as a chance floor. Source: d_personality_vs_codec.csv . Dimension Codec avg Persona Neutral entity_pronunciation − 0.16 -0.16 + 0.73 +0.73 − 0.05 -0.05 speech_clarity − 0.17 -0.17 + 0.08 +0.08 + 0.05 +0.05 prosody_naturalness − 0.13 -0.13 − 0.47 -0.47 − 0.12 -0.12 overall_fidelity + 0.09 +0.09 − 0.02 -0.02 − 0.20 -0.20 interruption_audio_quality + 0.15 +0.15 − 0.70 -0.70 + 0.25 +0.25 speaking_rate_adaptation − 0.24 -0.24 − 0.38 -0.38 − 0.09 -0.09 accent_dialect_handling 0.00 \\phantom{+}0.00 − 0.04 -0.04 + 0.04 +0.04 audio_clarity − 0.15 -0.15 − 0.12 -0.12 − 0.05 -0.05 | ⋅ | |\\cdot| mean 0.14 0.32 0.11 Table 12: Persona-vs-codec effect decomposition. Persona effect / / codec effect ratio averaged across the eight dimensions is 2.3; both exceed the neutral baseline of 0.11. Appendix C DSP Defect Implementations C.1 Parameter table Table 13 lists the parameter values used for each of the six adversarial defects. Each defect is applied to an isolated copy of the baseline WAV; the perturbed clip is then re-registered as a synthetic run in the evaluation backend and scored by both the LALM and the three human raters. Defect Parameter values clip Hard amplitude clipping at ± 0.85 \\pm 0.85 of peak amplitude applied to the agent (LEFT) channel; both channels’ peaks are preserved before clipping. Duration unchanged. dead_air A single random 200–800 ms silence inserted into the agent channel at a uniformly-random position between 20% and 80% of the session duration. Client channel unmodified in the same time window. snr_noise Additive Gaussian white noise scaled to yield SNR of − 2 -2 to − 8 -8 dB (uniformly sampled per session) relative to the loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel. Applied to both channels. sample_rate_mismatch Downsample the agent channel from 16 kHz to 8 kHz then upsample back to 16 kHz using linear interpolation; introduces characteristic aliasing artefacts. Duration and RMS preserved. truncate_utterance A single 150–400 ms segment of the agent channel is removed at a uniformly-random position between 30% and 70% of the session duration. The tail is spliced back with a 5 ms linear crossfade. Session duration reduced by the truncation length. mispronounce_overdub A short vowel-region segment (100–300 ms) in the agent channel is replaced with a length-matched vowel from a different phoneme drawn from a small candidate pool. Duration unchanged. Table 13: Adversarial defect parameters. All defects operate on the 16 kHz stereo WAV baselines and preserve total duration except where noted. C.2 Reference implementation The six defects are implemented as pure-Python functions taking a NumPy array of the stereo signal and returning a modified array of the same shape (except truncate_utterance , which returns a shorter array). Illustrative implementations for the four signal-domain defects (the two temporal-splicing defects are more verbose) are: import numpy as np SR = 16000 AGENT = 0 # LEFT channel (agent); RIGHT (1) is the client def clip(x, thr=0.85): \"\"\"Hard-clip the agent channel to a fraction of its peak.\"\"\" y = x.copy() peak = np.max(np.abs(y[:, AGENT])) y[:, AGENT] = np.clip(y[:, AGENT], -thr * peak, thr * peak) return y def snr_noise(x, snr_db): \"\"\"Add Gaussian noise at a target SNR (dB), relative to the loudest 500 ms window of the agent channel; noise on both.\"\"\" agent = x[:, AGENT] win = int(0.5 * SR) energy = np.convolve(agent ** 2, np.ones(win), mode=\"valid\") start = int(np.argmax(energy)) peak_rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(agent[start:start + win] ** 2)) noise_rms = peak_rms / (10 ** (snr_db / 20)) return x + np.random.normal(0, noise_rms, size=x.shape) def sample_rate_mismatch(x): \"\"\"8 kHz down/up-sample of the agent channel (linear interp).\"\"\" y = x.copy() agent = y[:, AGENT] down = agent[np.arange(0, len(agent), 2)] y[:, AGENT] = np.interp(np.arange(len(agent)), np.arange(len(down)) * 2, down) return y def dead_air(x, start_s, dur_s): \"\"\"Zero-fill a window on the agent channel.\"\"\" y = x.copy() s, e = int(start_s * SR), int((start_s + dur_s) * SR) y[s:e, AGENT] = 0.0 return y Truncation and mispronounce-overdub are implemented as splice-and-crossfade over source-and-donor phoneme regions; the full implementations are available in the reproducibility manifest (Appendix E ). Appendix D Statistical Methodology D.1 Krippendorff α \\alpha with ordinal weighting We compute α \\alpha with the ordinal difference function of Krippendorff [6], in which the disagreement between two ordinal ratings is a rank-based squared distance defined over the cumulative marginal category frequencies (not the raw squared difference ( v 1 − v 2 ) 2 (v_{1}-v_{2})^{2} , which is the interval metric). We use the reference krippendorff implementation. Values are reported in the main paper’s Table 1 as the “Krip. α \\alpha ” column. We warn readers that on ceiling-effect dimensions the observed disagreement approaches the expected chance disagreement, driving α \\alpha toward zero, or slightly negative, regardless of the high simple agreement on the same dimension. D.2 Newcombe-Wilson hybrid CIs on recall difference For each (defect, dimension) cell we form the LALM recall p ^ L = k L / n \\hat{p}_{L}=k_{L}/n and human recall p ^ H = k H / n \\hat{p}_{H}=k_{H}/n , where k L k_{L} and k H k_{H} are the counts of perturbed clips where the respective judge’s score drops by ≥ 1 \\geq 1 point relative to baseline and n n is the number of three-rater-covered perturbed clips for that cell. We compute the 95% CI on p ^ L − p ^ H \\hat{p}_{L}-\\hat{p}_{H} using Newcombe’s Method 10 (hybrid Wilson), which for two independent proportions combines the Wilson score CIs on each proportion into a lower bound L L and upper bound U U on the difference (see Newcombe [4], eqs. 12–14). A cell is flagged L &gt; &gt; H when L &gt; 0 L&gt;0 and H &gt; &gt; L when U &lt; 0 U&lt;0 . D.3 Paired-test robustness check Newcombe’s Method 10 treats the LALM and human recalls as two independent proportions, but they are in fact paired: both judges score the same perturbed clips. As a robustness check we re-tested each cell with an exact paired McNemar test on the per-clip discordant pairs (the clips one judge flags and the other does not). Under this stricter paired criterion, 2 of the 48 cells reach p &lt; 0.05 p&lt;0.05 , both in the Human &gt; &gt; LALM direction and both perfect 8-of-8-versus-0-of-8 splits: clip × \\times audio_clarity and snr_noise × \\times entity_pronunciation. The other five cells the Newcombe-Wilson intervals flagged do not survive the paired test at n ≤ 8 n\\leq 8 : three of the five have a 5-of-5 (or 5-of-7) discordant split, i.e. every discordant pair favors the same judge, but at this sample size an exact binomial test needs a perfectly unanimous split to clear p &lt; 0.05 p&lt;0.05 , so these read as underpowered directional misses rather than disconfirmed effects. This reinforces the main-text caution that the individual significant cells are hypotheses to confirm rather than established effects; only the two most extreme misses are robust to the paired analysis. D.4 Bootstrap parameters Confidence intervals on Spearman ρ \\rho between the LALM and each rater use non-parametric bootstrap with the following parameters: • Iterations: 1,000 • Resampling unit: session (i.e. all 8 dimensions of a resampled session travel together) • Sampling: with replacement • CI method: percentile (2.5%, 97.5%) • Random seed: 42 (documented in the analysis script) D.5 Human-human ρ \\rho confidence intervals Section 4.1 compares the bootstrap 95% CI of the LALM-human ρ \\rho (Table 5 ) against the CI of the human-human ρ \\rho , which is not tabulated elsewhere in this paper. Table 14 reports it, computed with the identical session-level resampling procedure described above, applied to the average of the three pairwise rater-rater correlations. On 7 of 8 dimensions the two intervals overlap; on audio_clarity they do not, which is why that dimension’s rank-correlation gap is treated as the one exception to the LALM-as-fourth-rater parity result. Source: rho_hh_ci.csv . Dimension ρ H ​ H \\rho_{HH} 95% CI ( ρ H ​ H \\rho_{HH} ) 95% CI ( ρ L ​ H \\rho_{LH} ) Overlap accent_dialect_handling + 0.08 +0.08 [ − 0.01 , + 0.29 ] [-0.01,+0.29] [ − 0.12 , + 0.17 ] [-0.12,+0.17] yes audio_clarity + 0.47 +0.47 [ + 0.34 , + 0.58 ] [+0.34,+0.58] [ + 0.00 , + 0.30 ] [+0.00,+0.30] no speech_clarity + 0.01 +0.01 [ − 0.05 , + 0.08 ] [-0.05,+0.08] [ + 0.04 , + 0.33 ] [+0.04,+0.33] yes entity_pronunciation + 0.09 +0.09 [ − 0.00 , + 0.21 ] [-0.00,+0.21] [ + 0.04 , + 0.32 ] [+0.04,+0.32] yes prosody_naturalness + 0.11 +0.11 [ + 0.02 , + 0.20 ] [+0.02,+0.20] [ + 0.03 , + 0.28 ] [+0.03,+0.28] yes interruption_audio_quality + 0.25 +0.25 [ + 0.16 , + 0.34 ] [+0.16,+0.34] [ + 0.03 , + 0.29 ] [+0.03,+0.29] yes speaking_rate_adaptation + 0.17 +0.17 [ + 0.08 , + 0.26 ] [+0.08,+0.26] [ + 0.02 , + 0.26 ] [+0.02,+0.26] yes overall_fidelity + 0.11 +0.11 [ + 0.02 , + 0.20 ] [+0.02,+0.20] [ − 0.13 , + 0.15 ] [-0.13,+0.15] yes Table 14: Bootstrap 95% confidence intervals on the human-human ρ \\rho (average of the three pairwise rater correlations) alongside the LALM-human ρ \\rho CI already reported in Table 5 . Both use the same 1,000-iteration, session-level, seed-42 procedure. D.6 Pre-registration status None of the analyses in this paper were pre-registered. The three-regime taxonomy, the LALM-as-fourth-rater test, and the adversarial-defect design were specified before data collection. The persona-vs-codec decomposition and the per-rater-idiosyncrasy observation were identified post-hoc during analysis; the paper treats them as observational. The specific 0.07 rank-correlation-gap threshold used to report “5 of 8 dimensions” in Section 4.1 was likewise chosen after inspecting the data (it falls in an observed gap between the fifth- and sixth-closest dimensions, 0.07 versus 0.12) rather than fixed in advance; Table 5 reports the full per-dimension gaps so a reader can apply a different threshold if preferred. Appendix E Reproducibility Manifest Analysis artefacts. Every table in this paper is derived from one of the thirteen CSV files listed below. File names refer to the layout of the supplementary archive that accompanies this paper on submission. File Sourced tables h1_per_dim.csv Tables 5 , 9 h1_per_dim_natural.csv Table 2 h1_per_dim_gemini35flash.csv Table 6 h1_per_dim_gemini31propreview.csv Table 7 cross_model_comparison.csv Table 3 rho_hh_ci.csv Table 14 lalm_as_4th_rater.csv Table 5 , Fig. 3 h2_per_config_per_dim.csv Table 10 h3_defect_recall_with_ci.csv Table 8 , Fig. 4 e_ceiling_collapse.csv Table 11 d_personality_vs_codec.csv Table 12 full_per_session.csv raw per-session ratings h3_defect_recall_3rater.csv pre-CI defect counts Prompt and schema source files. The LALM prompts (Appendix A.4 ) and their JSON schemas are reproduced verbatim from two production source files: speech_fidelity_prompt.py (AgentSpeechFidelity) and conversational_audio_quality.py (ConversationalAudioQuality). Both files are included in the supplementary archive. Data availability. The anonymised CSVs, LALM prompts, JSON schemas, analysis scripts, and rendered figures described above are publicly available as a Hugging Face Dataset at https://huggingface.co/datasets/armaan-sayyad/lalm-judge-validation-full-duplex [7], released under CC-BY-4.0 for the data and figures and Apache License 2.0 for the scripts and prompts. Rater identifiers in the raw CSVs have been anonymised to R1, R2, R3 and session identifiers have been replaced with stable hashes. Every headline number in the paper can be reproduced from the released CSVs using the accompanying scripts. The 60 perturbed adversarial clips (short, derivative WAVs) will be included in a subsequent v0.2 release pending final data-clearance review. Raw session recordings from the primary 209-session corpus will not be publicly released, as they contain production agent output governed by internal data-handling policy. Requests for restricted access from bona fide researchers will be considered on a case-by-case basis. Appendix F Notation Glossary • LALM : Large Audio Language Model (Gemini 2.5 Flash in this study). • ρ H ​ H \\rho_{HH} : pairwise human-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three rater pairs. • ρ L ​ H \\rho_{LH} : LALM-human Spearman rank correlation, averaged across the three (LALM, rater) pairs. Used in Appendix Table 5 and the LALM-as-fourth-rater comparison. • ρ L ​ H ¯ \\rho_{L\\bar{H}} : Spearman correlation between the LALM and the mean human rating H ¯ \\bar{H} (a single series, not an average of pairwise correlations). Used for the per-stratum and score-region tables, where per-cell n n is too small to average three pairwise correlations reliably. • H ¯ \\bar{H} : across-rater mean of the three human ratings on a session × \\times dimension. • % within 1 : proportion of sessions where the two ratings being compared differ by at most 1 Likert point. • recall (adversarial arm) : proportion of perturbed clips where the score drops by at least 1 point relative to the same clip’s baseline rating. • L &gt; &gt; H / H &gt; &gt; L : significance flag on a (defect, dimension) cell where the LALM (respectively humans) are more sensitive under a Newcombe-Wilson 95% CI on the recall difference. Experimental support, please view the build logs for errors. Generated by L A T E xml . Instructions for reporting errors We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile support. To report errors in the HTML that 