{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b83ec10708ef8c8f", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# AudioJudge: Understanding What Works in Large Audio Model Based Speech Evaluation\narXiv: 2507.12705\nAuthors: Potsawee Manakul, Woody Haosheng Gan, Michael J. Ryan, Ali Sartaz Khan, Warit Sirichotedumrong, Kunat Pipatanakul, William Held, Diyi Yang\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We provide a systematic study of AudioJudge across diverse speech evaluation tasks, demonstrating its strengths and weaknesses for evaluating both example-level audio characteristics and system-level performance.\n  2. We investigate prompt engineering strategies tailored for audio evaluation, introducing audio concatenation techniques that improve performance at both example and system levels, and a multi-aspect ensemble approach that improves correlation with human judgment.\n  3. We conduct thorough robustness checks finding that LAMs maintain stability under acoustic noise, but exhibit significant verbosity and positional biases that require mitigation.\n\nTags: Eval/LLM, LALM/理解型", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "bf0079f8-fad1-498d-b509-4e608c3c51ef", "uuid": "f9cd8dd4-c196-4822-af99-502dbf673338", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T17:53:48.620Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# AudioJudge: Understanding What Works in Large Audio Model Based Speech Evaluation\narXiv: 2507.12705\nAuthors: Potsawee Manakul, Woody Haosheng Gan, Michael J. Ryan, Ali Sartaz Khan, Warit Sirichotedumrong, Kunat Pipatanakul, William Held, Diyi Yang\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We provide a systematic study of AudioJudge across diverse speech evaluation tasks, demonstrating its strengths and weaknesses for evaluating both example-level audio characteristics and system-level performance.\n  2. We investigate prompt engineering strategies tailored for audio evaluation, introducing audio concatenation techniques that improve performance at both example and system levels, and a multi-aspect ensemble approach that improves correlation with human judgment.\n  3. We conduct thorough robustness checks finding that LAMs maintain stability under acoustic noise, but exhibit significant verbosity and positional biases that require mitigation.\n\nTags: Eval/LLM, LALM/理解型", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
